SP  - 267
EP  - 291
PY  - 1984
DA  - 1984/11/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3932(84)90044-8
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304393284900448
AB  - In this paper we propose and test a new explanation of bank behavior during the Free Banking Era, 1837–1863. Arguing against the conventional view that free bank failures were due to wildcat banking, we claim they were caused by falling asset prices. Confronting both explanations with our new and detailed data set developed from state auditor reports, we find that the falling asset price explanation of free bank failures explains far more failures than does the wildcatting hypothesis.
